segments.text: Mr. Pappas, would you please tell us a little bit about your personal background and some of your experiences before becoming involved with Mitchell Energy and the Woodlands Corporation, and then explain how you happened to be here today, I suppose.
First of all, I came to this country back in 1946.
My parents were Americans.
I and my younger brothers were born in Greece.
And we were there during the war.
Immediately after the war, we came back.
I had finished high school there.
And I went to the University of Missouri for my arrival back to the States.
And I got a degree in civil engineering from there.
And then they took me in the army.
And I spent a couple of years in Germany.
And when I came back, I worked in New York where I got married.
And I went overseas for the employers that I worked for two or three times.
And in 1962, I got a job with a New York developer.
And they sent me here to Texas.
And that's when I met Mr. Mitchell.
Now your specialty, your work had been in what area as an engineer?
In highway design and land development.
Had you been involved in any major real estate or new community type projects?
No.
No, I had never been involved in new communities.
Development, in fact, when we were thinking about the woodlands as a new community, Mr. Mitchell and I
We had discussions as to how we can put a team together to do it.
And he asked me point blank if I had done it in town before.
I said, no.
He said, neither have I. I said, so we're both going to learn together, aren't we?
And we've got to pay for it, too.
How did you make the Mitchell connection originally?
How did that happen?
When I came here with a developer from New York, Mr. Mitchell and the partner of his by the name Norman Dobbins,
They were involved in housing.
They had a company by the name of Pace Center Homes.
And Mr. Dobbins was very active with the Houston Home Builders Association.
He was the president, in fact, when I arrived here in town.
What year was that?
And as a prospective developer, the first
entity that I knocked at its door.
It was the Home Builders Association, Mr. Dobbins was the president.
And he told me that he would be interested in knowing what we're doing down here as far as development is concerned.
And he introduced me to Mr. Mitchell.
And Mr. Mitchell turned around and says to me, you people have the land.
I have the development or the housing company.
And I have the oil and gas.
You people have shipping.
So see if you can put something together for us.
And then we had the company I was with.
We had a piece of property, which just immediately still is, immediately south of the Woodlands, where the Woodlands is today.
1,400 acres of land.
And we had another 2,000 acres of land down by where Bay, oops, the big shopping center down by Webster Runs.
Oh, near Cherry?
Baybrook.
Baybrook.
Yeah, Baybrook Mall.
OK. 2,000 acres there.
And of course, we had about 15 acres of land across the street from the Shamrock Hotel.
And that's where I came down here to develop.
from New York.
And we did an economic survey and analysis of three tracts of land, and with an outfit from California.
And they suggested that it was quite premature for this tract of land south of the woodlands to be developed.
If we felt like war was imminent and that the defense industry would be very active, then the property south of Houston, the Web Surround, ought to be developed.
Not much of NASA was by that time.
And you knew NASA was coming.
Not when we had the money.
We put the earnest money down.
No, we did not launch at NASA.
That was in August 1961.
In November 1961, the NASA site was announced, and we closed the property the 23rd of December of the same year.
Nobody did not know that NASA would be located.
In any way, they told us that if we felt like war was imminent, that the defense contractor would be hefty, then that site down there would be developed.
However, they felt that it would be one industry-oriented type of a site, and that we'd be very, very careful how we develop it.
Because at any rate, at any time where the Defense Department felt that they were overspending themselves, they would cut it down.
And therefore, you're going to be out.
They recommended that we go ahead and develop the site across the street from Shamrock.
However, it was not a large enough site to create an organization around.
Yeah, that was just a couple hundred acres or something?
No, that was 15 acres.
Oh, I see.
43 from Shamrock.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
And then I went back to New York.
I developed a high-rise apartment building for the corporation.
And then I happened to come down here on New Year's Eve party in 1966.
And I, of course, I had a lot of friends by that time here in Houston, Mr. Dobbins, Mr. Mitchell.
And I went up there to say hello to him.
By that time, of course, he had accumulated all this land over here.
And we talked to each other about moving down here.
At the party.
That's right.
No, not at the party.
After the party.
Yeah.
In fact, this property over here that Mr. Mitchell purchased, it was offered to us in New York.
by a realtor by the name Weisberger, Ernest Weisberger.
And I called my boss.
He was in London at that time.
He says, I'm coming home, he says, for Thanksgiving.
We'll go down to Houston, have a look at the properties.
By that time, the Mitchell had persisted.
And when I came down here for the party, I went up to his office to see him.
Congratulated him on the purchase, and we talked about it a little bit.
Before I knew it, I came back to Houston.
That's a good story.
That's the way things happen.
Well, they didn't, up to that point, they did not have a civil engineer at all.
And they were doing, at that time, they were doing, as far as development is concerned, Pirates Beach and Pirates Falls.
They were doing that at that time.
Do you work on those projects as well?
Do you work on those projects?
Oh, yes, absolutely.
And also this facility in Aspen?
Yes, I work on that, too.
So your responsibility is for?
Engineering, construction, all the real estate.
All the real estate, OK. For the corporation.
And in 1967, June 1,
I moved my rear end over here.
I hope that, oh, you have to keep that up.
We'll edit it and give it back to you.
I hope the hell you leave it.
Where did you live?
Where did you move to?
There was no woodland.
Did you live in this vicinity?
Oh, no.
Physically?
I still don't live here.
Oh, you don't?
No, sir.
I live in Houston.
And there's a story behind that.
Yeah, I like good stories.
Please do.
When, well, okay.
Parenthetically then, when we start putting the application for HUD together, back in 1970, 71, 72, 71 primarily.
As I said earlier, Mr. Mitchell had never built a new town, neither had I.
So we're going to spend some money in Water West to learn, and some other people, like Macalester, Jim Macalester was around at the time, some other people.
So we had gone to Macalester.
Mr. Mitchell and I were going to Columbia, Maryland.
That was the first generation of New Towns.
And from there, we went to the rest of Virginia, which was the counterpart.
And Columbia had a population at that time about, oh, I would say about 7,000 to 10,000 people.
And of course, Mr.
Rouse, Jim Rouse, was very, very generous with his information.
He might have instructed his key people to open up his books, you know, any information that he needed to go ahead and share it with us.
and invited us to an open meeting with his employees down at Pavilion, very similar to the Cynthia Good Mitchell Pavilion they had there, who were his guests.
I spent three, four, five days there at one time or the other.
And what impressed me was in Colombia, of course, it was not socially, it was very active.
for the small number of people that they had down there.
We used to go to the bar that they had on the high rise by the lake there.
And we'd see a lot of women there, men there, messing around, moving around.
In discussions, of course, I found out that Colombia was over-planned.
Colombia was planned in such a way as that taking all the initiative away from the individual.
They had it organized such a way as the paint job would be done by an organization, you know, home properties.
The yard would be mined in a certain way by the homeowners association.
It was too structured.
And left a lot of time in the hands of individuals, wives and husbands.
And they, some people, although you had to pay for all the services.
Sure.
And when those costs started hitting the pocketbook, a lot of them, they could not necessarily be, were able to afford it.
And that brought frictions and tremendous divorce rates.
He said, in fact, I asked Mr. Ted Baker, who was the head planner for Columbia at that time, what the hell... That's trouble in paradise.
Yeah, what the hell happened here?
He says, well, I suggest, he says, I recommend, never live in the place where you work.
That really sunk in very, very heavily, because 98% divorce rate, the people who work there, they start messing around in the same environment, you know.
And they never really separated their social life from the business life.
From the business and their family life.
And really impressive.
98% divorce rate.
That's incredible.
They were all young people of course.
They were all young professionals trying to make it.
And that impressed me in the negative.
That is impressive.
Something what not to do over here.
Did that idea though enter into at all the planning
I wasn't really in development at all.
Yes, it was proposed.
It was set into our plan of thinking.
However, more so in my own plan, my own family plan.
But you don't want to overdo it.
Yeah, sure.
I see that.
And I said at that time, there's a lot to be said about dividing or separating your social life with your business life and your family.
That's right.
And that's why I still don't .
But that's a good analysis, too.
And a good comparison of this community and the area.
And of course, for the woodlands, I personally believe the woodlands are not over planned.
I don't either.
I was just wondering.
It needs to be in the hands of the property owners to do their own thing inside and out.
Yeah.
For that opportunity, at least.
Now, in the development of the terrain, the geography, the drainage, and so forth, you were instrumental in planning that initial development, weren't you?
I'm doing it.
Yes, sir.
What is that?
I haven't seen one, but if you had a job description, what would it say?
Me?
Yeah.
I'm an officer in charge of engineering and construction.
And that was from the beginning.
That basically was your job description.
And that's remained constant?
Yes.
OK. Now, what kind of a perception or precept or idea or goal did you have when you went into the woodlands to set this up as a habitable
Well, we had at least, first name Henry, right?
Right.
We had, I would say, two or three years worth of very heavy interchange of ideas with consultants.
We visited numerous sites in order to see how they were doing and what they were doing wrong.
in order to have that as an input, at least on a large scale, to our community.
From a physical plan, nothing very much changed.
You need to provide adequate drainage in order to avoid flooding.
People love to see the rain, sitting in their living room, rain, beautiful water.
But when they start feeling the water through the torch going from one door through the
to the other door, they don't particularly care for that.
Yeah, a lot of the charm wears off.
Sir?
A lot of the charm wears off.
Well, I think the headaches are setting in.
So they do need adequate drainage.
People do not necessarily want to see the water flow down like rivers.
They don't mind seeing the water standing like that, for example, here.
However, when the water starts getting into their homes, then the problem with that.
So you need to provide that with drainage.
Secondly, people really don't care where you get it from as long as every time the faucet water comes out.
And more than they care where the electricity comes from.
They want the results of the care.
And once they use that water, really nobody wants to be around the area where the water has to be treated.
Either they want to stay away from it.
They don't want to see it.
They want to see it coming out, but they want to flush it out.
They have nothing to do with it.
So by the time you start thinking of all those things put together, and then how to conserve those natural resources, then it becomes an area where you need a lot of specialists.
And to that, we have to rely very heavily
in what technology, at that time, the prevailing technology had to offer us.
For example, in the very beginning of the woodlands, we thought we were going to do something that nobody else had done.
Purify the water that comes out to the degree that you might want to reuse it.
We convinced some of the federal agents up there, and they granted some
and some grants, gave us some grants in order to promote that.
And we did.
The first increment of the sewer plant that we did over here in the Woodlands, we imposed upon ourselves the restrictions that the Water Quality Board, Texas, and EPA at that time sought.
And they told us it's not necessary.
However, we imposed that upon ourselves.
And we have already the increment of the infrastructure in.
in order to resupply the lakes with ethanol from the .
And we were the first ones to go ahead and install an ozonator.
Ozon has a tremendous kill power as far as bacteria is concerned, but dissipates very quickly.
But the state law and the federal law says that when you dump ethanol
into a creek, the receiving stream has to show a residual chlorine, which is a disinfectant, for 20 minutes.
That's it.
Well, ozone, although it has 10 times the kill power that chlorine has, dissipates, however, very quickly.
And therefore, once you start analyzing the sample, you're not going to find any residual.
So we have to overcome that.
So what we did, we killed with ozone, and then we threw in some chlorine in order for the agency to find the residual down below.
To meet the requirement.
That's correct.
Which is, it was kind of, that's paranoia, you know.
And you had demonstration plans up in Washington, D.C. that I went to, without chemicals.
It was demonstrating to the federal agency down there how to kill with ozone and pure oxygen.
And in fact, we drank from them effluent.
You know, after it came out, we drank it.
We went up to Tahoe, Tahoe, Nevada, yeah.
And they had the same, because they were prohibited in discharging effluent into Lake Tahoe.
Prohibited.
So they had to go over the mountain 28 miles with a horseman and create lakes there.
And then ozonate up there and some rainbow trout this big.
And they had the same principle.
But over here, we have to show residuals.

And when we came in to expand for the second time, EPA, the people who gave us the grants originally, said, now look, if you want our money, if you want our money to enlarge your plant, now you have to reduce your standards.
More pollutants.
Introducing the streams, more pollutants.
And that's what we have.
Those are the inconsistencies.
In other words, what they're telling you, it was a good thought, a good idea.
However, it became very expensive in order to do that.
Now, if you want our grants and you reduce your standards, then for the same amount of money, we can get twice as much of the product.
That's what they're telling you.
So instead of having the residual
contaminants to be 10 parts per million, 10 parts per million, 10 parts per million.
They say now you can have 20 parts per million, 20 parts per million, 20 parts per million contaminants in the effluent coming out.
Because in order to reduce, to take the last 5%, 5% out, it requires double the amount of money, or triple maybe.
Because now they're getting down to the refinements, filtration, and you know.
of a very high tech type of treatment.
Tertiary treatment, really, that's what I'm talking about.
And they were saying, excuse me for a minute, not to conclude it.
They say to you that since the stream does not require, is healthy enough not to require this extensive treatment, therefore reduce the amount of treatment so we can do without that high expense.
So we have reduced it.
But your basic plan was very, you might say, progressive or,
way ahead of anybody else's.
There was nothing else, especially in the state, definitely.
Lake Tahoe had one.
Lake Tahoe.
Tahoe, the seat of Tahoe had one, and of course there was an experimental thing down in Washington, D.C., and we were not advanced.
Well, did this come primarily through your consultants or through you, this conception?
No, it was a joint
type of thinking through a round table type of discussions.
He was a Mr. Rice University, the environmental engineering department.
He was acting as our consultant.
A guy by the name of .
He was a PhD in industrial waste.
And he was the person who originally designed conceptually.
SMB engineers from Houston, who are engineers with petrochemical industry, designed the actual plant, SMB engineers.
And it was built by LEM, L-E-M, contractors.
What was your main job then, once you began to develop the plot and the plan, I guess, primarily contracting and letting out contracts and supervising the construction and so forth?
Those are contracts.
Yeah.
I just signed them today.
This is what ensured the contracts for them.
I've been reading about that, yes.
This over here, yes.
$327 million job.
And this also is $370 million job.
A million books?
Yeah.
$370 million.
Each one of them.
Those are for infrastructure facilities that water, sewer, and drainage pipe on the ground.
What I was speaking before is the capacity in the plant.
Right.
That's interesting.
What changes have been wrought or created
as this first phase of the Woodlands begins to transition from operation by the Woodlands Corporation to operation by the local citizenry?
How is that going to affect what you do, or will it at all?
Well, it will not.
It will not.
Because what you are referring to, I believe, correct me if I'm
open the tenure, you're talking about the WCA taking over.
Community association.
Yeah, community association taking over.
The community association really has nothing to do with the development process.
The development process, that is totally in the hands of the developer, the Woodland Corporation.
The community association will
operate and manage all the public facilities other than wet utilities.
They will operate the parks, they will operate the lakes, maintain and operate the lakes.
So in other words, the Woodlands Corporation will retain control and operative management of, like, the utility districts and...
The utility district, of course, that's more or less like a semi-corporation.
It's a public entity.
The members of the board are elected by the people that they serve.
So it is more or less the governmental entity.
That's what it is.
WCA will have the responsibility of operating and maintaining
public facilities like parks, like pedestrian, you know, bike and kite trails, and common areas, common areas to own.
That's the kind of a function they have.
Also, they have a function in architectural controls whereby if you want to enlarge your house, if you want to alter, you know, your property, you have to go through that kind of a
a review, architectural review committee, in order to be able to alter, make changes.
And that's the function WCA has.
Back in 1992, the Woodlands would lose the majority vote in that organization.
That's what you're referring to.
That has nothing to do with the development process.
The land development process is a part that's happened from it.
This is where we take excuse.
And where we take the raw land, the raw land, and we transform it, we develop it to the point that will receive a dwelling unit or a store on the, you know, the above ground type of facility.
When you do that, incidentally, do you contract out surveyors and those sub kind of, in other words, there's not an in-house facility?
of people to do that.
No.
Let me give you the process, you know, that we follow through.
When we break up, when we project that our needs, and we have a five-year projection.
The first year is much more definite than the fifth year.
We say that we are going to produce next five years
5,000 lots.
We'll have 300 acres of commercial real estate and the likes.
We have our planners that set up with, of course, with the marketing people, input of whatever they prognosticate.
Of course, we have a market analysis first.
That's the first thing.
What the hell is the market going to be like for the next five years on a per year basis?
Most definitely, again, the first year and then
next five years.
And we say to ourselves, all right, now we're going to develop these thousand acres next year out of these 5,000 acres.
In order to develop these 5,000 acres, you cannot look at one year at a time because some facilities, they take more than one year to design, let alone to build.
So we have, in our midst, we have a schedule of things that we need to do.
For example,
how to provide water for the facilities.
If I am to develop 1,000 lots next year, or 5,000 lots altogether, I would need the equivalent of two wells to drill, to drill two wells.
To drill two wells will cost me half a million dollars, only for the wells.
Now, to bring that water into a central plant to disinfect
and put it in storage.
Then it would require an elevated storage tank of about half a million dollars.
Half a million gallons, half a million dollars worth.
And then booster pumps in order to have the water pressure when I deliver it to your house, at least with 60 pound pressure.
So I have to push it through the booster pump.
So the whole thing might cost me about $2 million.
And I need two years to build in order
to provide for you two years hence.
Two years hence.
And then, of course, that followed.
If you don't build a storage tank only to accommodate 1,000 lots, you've got to build for 5,000.
So you have some elements of the infrastructure that out there are waiting for the future development.
When you build a sewer plant, you don't build for one year synchronously.
It takes you through the permitting process.
It takes you two or three years.
So you can see how ahead of yourself you have to be.
Put a lot up front, money and planning and everything else.
Yeah.
And that is small amounts.
The planning and the engineering part ahead of development is a small amount.
Once you start getting into the ground with 56-inch diameter pipes and 72-inch pipes, six feet.
taller than you are.
You can see 20 feet in the ground.
You can see how much.
Because you're not going to put a 12-inch pipe in there to accommodate only that subdivision.
You've got to think ahead and see what else is going to be coming in to this .
This more or less will demonstrate more.
Can I pick it up there?
Yeah, I think so.
so you will understand what your evidence is.
When we first started thinking about the woodlands, we looked at it, you know, how we're going to service it.
So at that time, the thinking in the engineering profession was when you have the possibility of contaminating something by breakdown, you will be better off
to happen in small increments.
So it's very unlikely that you're going to have a breakdown in more than one unit.

Therefore, if you are going to produce, say, 30 million gallons per day, ultimately, 30 million gallons per day effluent, if you have it all located in one place and you have a breakdown, 30 million gallons a day of untreated sewer will come down as a big slug.
What are you going to do?
You can't stop it.
People are going to keep flushing their toilets, whether the plant works or not.
So the thinking back there was to break it down to smaller increments.
So if we have one break down, we're going to have 5 million gallons, and 30 million gallons go astray.
And so the thinking at that time was to have about two or three sewer plants on Spring Creek, and then have another two or three down on Panther Creek, which is this destination.
And that's how we proceeded at that time.
However, very quickly, it became apparent that with all the safeguards that we have, it's very unlikely that you're going to have a major breakdown, even in a large plan.
Because in a large plan, the economy works in your favor.
And then with a large plan,
you can afford to do other things that you cannot afford to do in small plants.
Redundant systems.
That is correct.
That is correct.
Like, for example, auxiliary power.
If you have a breakdown, say, with commercial power of the utilities, then you can have an auxiliary power.
And because of those things, it became very apparent later on, and that would be engineering thinking of the time.
And then now we have it down to sewer plants, to major plants for the woodlands.
One will be something like 12 million gallons per day, ultimately.
And another one will be about 18 million gallons per day.
Follow me?
Yeah.
Now, because of their location, because of their location, one would be located or would have already been designed to be located in this place over here, like the 18 million gallon plant.
Like you can see, you see what will have to, will serve all this area of the .
Therefore, the first piece of pipe that you put over here will have to be large enough to accommodate it.
Everything that comes in and out of there.
You follow me?
Sure.

The other way around now, if you were going to develop over here and the location was over here, then you develop over here, now you have to string all these pipes all the way down there because the first, how is it served, has to be connected to the sewer plant.
So you see that the economics, you know,
dictate that you go from the low land to the upper land.
Oh, because of that.
All right.
Did, in, say, the first phase of development, say, through the 1970s, did basically the planning match the reality?
Did things develop as you thought they should, pretty much?
Yeah, in a much slower pace.
Yeah, OK. Our projections at that time
Of course, the economy of this region over here, there was no stopping.
Whatever you put down on the ground, it was sold with a profit, whether you knew how to do it or not.
The market was so healthy.
And we were thinking of finishing up the wilderness in 20 years, 20, 30 years maximum.
We knew, of course, there would be remnants, strategically located parcels of property.
that we would not get to as far as marketing is concerned, but those values that were going up.
So we thought the development process would finish in about 20, 30 years.
But that was one of the assumptions we had made back then that did not materialize.
Other than the pace, has there been much change in direction in the planning and processes?
Not very much.
Not very much at all.
Yes, there are some refinements that we found to be more acceptable in the marketplace.
Like what?
We're market-driven.
Whatever product we create and we manufacture has to be sold, has to be accepted in the marketplace.
For example, what?
We thought that we would have small, narrow, private streets with open ditches for drainage, for example.
The marketplace dictates something different.
They want you to have
curb and gutter streets, especially in the streets that they front on the house, where the house fronts to.
You can go down to Memorial area, and you'll find that open ditches are acceptable.
However, we thought the same thing over here.
However, we do not, this area, the Woodlands is not Memorial.
We don't have the large lots that we, you know, down there.
I have a lot down there, one and a quarter acres.
Here, when you have a 50, 60, 70-foot lot, and you have open ditches, then you have a conglomeration of little culverts, you know.
And that will be 20 feet.
That will be a third of your lot from it, or something similar to that.
And then every 60 feet or 50 feet, you have another one, just like that.
And you can see, you know, that will not be conducive to a nice environment.
So those are the things that we learned, you know, from the marketplaces.
Of course, our major thoroughfares, they're still open beaches.
The original principle of slowing the water down and make an amenity out of this water conveyance system still persists here in the wilderness today.
However, those are the small things, refinement, that I'm speaking of, like curve .
What was the rationale behind the paving bricks at the intersection?
Oh, that's a visual amenity.
That's all the arrival aesthetics.
Strictly aesthetic.
In order to give you a notion of arrival.
Now, pay attention.
You have arrived to a different kind of a place.
It's nice.
When you move into the 80s now, say, 83, 84, the economy has turned down around here.
Could you sort of explain what's happening here in the 1980s and what your work is and how it may have differed, say, from earlier activities?
We started playing very, very close to the vest.
Then our projections, they were a little bit more conservative.
because we knew that the market was not here.

We were reacting, and we were able to react to the market more so than anybody else because we, at that time, we decided, Mr. Mitchell decided, management decided, to be ready to respond to the market needs.
And therefore, we had our engineering done in advance.
We had our plans done in advance when there was a need
for a specific type of a product to be put out in the marketplace, we're able to react very quickly.
Because the woodland is not a subdivision.
It's not a 20x subdivision.
It's not a 100x subdivision.
It's not a 300x subdivision, where the subdiviser will say, now I'm going to have a product over here, 65 foot large, 120 foot in depth, and I'm going to have the product
to market from $120,000 to $150,000.
That's not the kind of an area we have over here.
We have anywhere from low cost housing and apartments and town houses all the way to estates.
There might be better than 25 type of categories that we have to produce.
Now to have inventory, readily made inventory for all those 25 types of lots, 22 types of lots that you have.
And to maintain a readily made inventory, that would be at even, say, $10,000 per lot.
You are out there $20 million at any one time.
Money is waiting for the marketplace.
And that can be very strange.
At 10% interest per year, you're talking about $2 million in interest that you're paying on inventory that is sitting there.
So we are left with a lot of time to be able to respond to the market.
And having done
And having done the engineering, within 90 days, I think, we could be in production.
Yeah.
But now you, there was a distinct turnaround here earlier than most places.
In fact, you never lost the kind of market loss that other areas in Houston did in terms of housing.
No.
That's correct.
We did not feel the impact as heavily as they did.
Because we were able, we had the market over here that had all kinds of
It was across the spectrum.
It was very wide.
While those people, they were reflecting to one market or the other.
And of course, we were selling over here a way of life.
We were not selling a lot of house.
We were selling a way of life.
And I think that was more acceptable to the little, weak market that was there.
